<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 9:4<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I288e2b10630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>9.</label.designator><headtext>Hearsay</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id7203e34682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>9:4.</label.designator><headtext>Hearsay within hearsay</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017163" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-805" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I3a624ab07fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-805</cite.query> provides:</paratext><display.quote><para><paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>Hearsay included within hearsay shall not be excluded under the hearsay rule if each part of the combined statements conforms with an exception to the hearsay rule.<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/></paratext></para></display.quote><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017163" w-serial-number="2036633058" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000960" ID="I3a62e6f37fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Tuggle v. Rose,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic4ed84107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] the court held inadmissible an investigator&apos;s report which included summaries of statements made by a child&apos;s classmates regarding an incident where the child was restrained by a teacher. <eos/><bos/>The respondents in a summary judgment motion provided an exception to the first layer of hearsay, but failed to provide an exception to the second.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017163" w-serial-number="2017439912" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3a63f8627fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Sullivan v. State</ital></cite.query>, the court held that a mother&apos;s testimony that her child told her that the defendant made another child have sex with him was double hearsay that did not qualify for admission under the child hearsay statute.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic4ed84117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Likewise, the Court held that while outgoing text messages from a defendant were admissible as admissions by a party op<page no="284"/>ponent, the incoming texts were subject to a double hearsay objection.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic4ed84127fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>On the other hand, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017163" w-serial-number="2040218419" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3a6530e27fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Robbins v. State,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic4ed84137fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court held double hearsay admissible after a police officer testified at trial that a witness informed the officer that the victim told the witness about a severe beating that just occurred at the hands of the defendant. <eos/><bos/>The Court first found that the witness&apos;s out-of-court statement to the officer was not hearsay under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017163" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-613" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I3a661b407fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-6-613</cite.query> because the witness testified at the trial, was subject to cross-examination, and the statement was offered as a prior inconsistent statement to the witness&apos;s testimony at trial that the victim told her that her injuries were caused by a fall. <eos/><bos/>Next, the Court found that the victim&apos;s statements to the witness were admissible under the excited utterance exception to hearsay.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Similarly, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017163" w-serial-number="2038599084" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3a6669627fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Mosley v. State,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic4edab207fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] the Supreme Court upheld the admission of double hearsay in a criminal case where the defendant first failed to object at trial. <eos/><bos/>Examining the facts under a plain error rule, the Court held the double hearsay admissible because the state was rehabilitating a witness under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017163" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-613" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I3a6705a07fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A § 24-6-613</cite.query>, and further the defendant had opportunity to cross-examine the declarant at trial.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>It is well settled that officers may rely on hearsay and even hearsay upon hearsay to furnish the basis for the issuance of valid warrants.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic4edab217fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic4ed84107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017163" w-serial-number="2036633058" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000960" ID="I3a6335137fc011ea988285db8533e975">Tuggle v. Rose, 333 Ga. App. 431, 773 S.E.2d 485, 319 Ed. Law Rep. 586 (2015)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic4ed84117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017163" w-serial-number="2017439912" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3a641f727fc011ea988285db8533e975">Sullivan v. State, 295 Ga. App. 145, 671 S.E.2d 180 (2008)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="284"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic4ed84127fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017163" w-serial-number="2045869663" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3a6494a27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Johnson v. State, 347 Ga. App. 831, 821 S.E.2d 76 (2018)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic4ed84137fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017163" w-serial-number="2040218419" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3a6557f27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Robbins v. State, 300 Ga. 387, 793 S.E.2d 62 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic4edab207fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017163" w-serial-number="2038599084" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3a66b7827fc011ea988285db8533e975">Mosley v. State, 298 Ga. 849, 785 S.E.2d 297 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic4edab217fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017163" w-serial-number="2034833401" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3a677ad27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Shirley v. State, 330 Ga. App. 424, 765 S.E.2d 491 (2014)</cite.query>, <case.history>judgment rev&apos;d on other grounds</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017163" w-serial-number="2037156539" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3a677ad57fc011ea988285db8533e975">297 Ga. 722, 777 S.E.2d 444 (2015)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="285"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 9:4<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
